    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-04-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-04-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="1061"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1061">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.11/3726a.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to all
                            <gloss type="to">American Consuls in Mexico</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-04-22">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 22, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In pursuance of the President’s purpose to enforce amends for indignities
                    offered, the naval commander at Vera Cruz took possession of the customhouse,
                    cable office, post office, and telegraph and railroad terminals which were
                    directly connected with the customs collection. Immediately thereafter an attack
                    upon our marines was begun by unorganized bands of Mexicans, whose fire drew our
                    men into a general contest, and it became necessary in order to establish peace
                    in Vera Cruz to take the whole city. Up to eight o’clock last night four
                    American soldiers were killed and twenty wounded. This Government will advise
                    those in command that this Government does not desire to interfere with civil
                    government at Vera Cruz.</p>
                <p>In view of the present critical situation, you are instructed to urge all
                    Americans to leave Mexico as soon as possible.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
